subSubSection.paragraph:
Variability of cephalic and pronotal armament
. More developed males (
Fig. 14
) bear a clypeal horn inclined forward in its proximal half (
Fig. 18
), shorter than the interocular distance, situated forward of the head midlength. Its apex is clearly round, sometimes with a groove in its ventral side, and slightly curved backward. The pronotum has a nearly vertical anterior declivity with the upper edge bent downward at sides, that bears two blunt, sometimes transverse prominences close together, separated by the length of one of them or more, and a vertical very feeble crest on each side (
Fig. 16
).

In specimens with minor development (
Fig. 17
), the cephalic horn is shorter, female-like, and the pronotum is almost declivitous anteriorly, with the two anteromedian gibbosities vestigial.

Females (
Fig. 15
) have a more or less short, transverse, slightly elevated clypeal carina truncate at its summit and feebly pointed on each side, and a slight, straight, transverse carina just behind the pronotal front margin, which sometimes shows trace of median prominences.

Aedeagus
. Parameres in lateral view slender (
Fig. 20
), gradually tapering toward apex, which is round in dorsal view (
Fig. 19
). Ventral side is apically hairless.

